04315nam a22005535i 9780774850179DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748501797 a10.59962/97807748501792doi  a(DE-B1597)662288  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ242.55.A5bJ43 2002eb 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a363.4/4/095931 aJeffrey, Leslie Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSex and Borders :bGender, National Identity and Prostitution Policy in Thailand /cLeslie Ann Jeffrey. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGender, Prostitution, and the “Standards of Civilization” -- tPeasants, Prostitutes, and the Body Politic: Prostitution as Cultural Decline and Political Resistance in the 1960s and 1970s -- tElite Women, the Reconstruction of National Identity, and the Prostitution Problem -- tWomen’s Groups and the Prostitution Question: Prostitution Law under Premocracy -- tThe Politics of Prostitution and the “New Man”: The 1996 Prostitution Law, International Image, and Middle-Class Masculinity -- tThe Middle Class and the Material Girl: The 1996 Prostitution Law and the Disciplining of Peasant Women -- tThe Politics of Prostitution: Gender, Class, and Nation -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProstitution in Thailand has been the subject of media sensationalism for decades. Bangkok's brothels have become international icons of "third world" women's exploitation in the global sex trade. Recently, however, sex workers have begun to demand not pity, but rights as workers in the global economy. This book explores how Thai national identity in such an economy is linked to prostitution and gender. Jeffrey asserts that certain images of "The Prostitute" have silenced discourses of prostitution as work, while fostering the idea of the peasant woman as the embodiment of national culture. This idea, coupled with a will to shape the modern state through the behaviour of middle-class men, has been a main concern of Thai prostitution policy. Gender, Jeffrey argues, has become the mechanism through which states respond to the contradictory pressures of globalization and nation-building. Sex and Borders is essential reading for those interested in gender studies, Southeast Asian studies, and the politics of prostitution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aProstitutionxHistoirexThaïlande. 0aProstitutionxHistoryxThailand. 0aProstitutionzThailandxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485017940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850179/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles